arch:property.oc:show_val: This material did not come in together, but rather in dribs and drabs over a month; therefore the analysis and numbering may be a bit disjointed. A medium-sized unit. Less than 10% burning, generally fresh looking, very little visible digestion. Some large (15-20 cm) pieces. Long bone fragments generally longer than normal. Some cattle-sized bone, especially many skull fragments (weathered condition, but this is probably due to recent exposure), also long bone, two ribs, a distal humerus, an equid scapula, and an extremely large cattle atlas fragment. Sheep-size bone is more plentiful; including long bone, ribs, teeth, phalanges. There were three fragments of identifiable bird bone. A nearly complete human scapula was in with the animal bone; it is possibly post-Neolithic, and not part of the scattered female skeleton that the human bone lab has found in this unit. It was the largest and freshest of all the bone in the unit. There is also a human axis (second vertebra) which may belong to the Neolithic female. The unit is similar to the middeny material around 2296. LY 2001: Additional material was studied in 2001, fragmentation was average, sheep/goat was the most common species but cattle and pig are also present. A significant proportion of the material was made up of a fragmented caprine skull and one scapula came from a fairly large animal. A fragmented pubis and a fibula belonging to a human was pulled. 4mm flotation samples 5 and 13 were recorded for diagnostics only. Last number = 286

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
